      "is_optimal": false,
      "approve": true,
      "feedback": "The plan will correctly restrict access to the backup shadow file and eliminate the reported permission issue. Using chmod 0000 is more restrictive than the STIG recommendation but still safe because root can bypass permissions. Consider using a less extreme mode (e.g., 0400) to align exactly with the STIG and to avoid potential issues with backup utilities that may need to read the file.",
      "concerns": [
        "Setting permissions to 0000 is overly restrictive and could interfere with scripts or backup tools that expect at least read access for privileged users."
      ],
      "suggested_improvements": [
        "Apply chmod 0400 /etc/shadow- to match the STIG recommendation while still protecting the file.",
        "Add a post\u2011change verification step (e.g., ls -l /etc/shadow-) to confirm the permissions were applied correctly.",
        "Document the change in the system's security hardening log for audit purposes."
      ],
